<comment datatype='string'>Baljinder et al. showed that NanR, NagC, and IHF activate &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;gene expression, but they could not determine which of the three promoters (fimBp1, fimBp2, fimBp3) is affected [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17238917&quot;&gt;Sohanpal07&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15534208&quot;&gt;Sohanpal04&lt;/a&gt;], and none could demonstrate which is the transcription activation mechanism. They concluded that the activation from NagC and IHF could be indirect, altering the DNA structure of the intergenic region between &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;nanC&lt;/i&gt;. Another possibility of activating the system is through direct contact of NagC with RNA polymerase [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17238917&quot;&gt;Sohanpal07&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15534208&quot;&gt;Sohanpal04&lt;/a&gt;]. 
&lt;p&gt;
There are three potential transcription start sites.   Transcription starting from two of the sites (P1 and P2) would  produce an mRNA that approximates the transcript size of &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt; previously detected by Northern blot hybridizations.</comment>
